"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005745","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-20","<p>The number of flight crew licence applications received by the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) has grown by more than 25 per cent this year. The CAA has responded by recruiting and training more licensing officers, increasing overtime, and pre-screening applications to ensure all the required information has been received. The CAA is also working with key stakeholders to identify improvements which will help to simplify and speed up the application process for both commercial and private pilots.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005745/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-20T16:02:08.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005745/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005745/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-11-12","Aviation: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to speed up the process by which the Civil Aviation Authority issues private pilots' licenses.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","190385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005746","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-20","<p>I am advised by the Industrial Injuries Advisory Council (IIAC) which is a non-Departmental public body made up of independent experts, representatives of employers and employees on matters relating to the Industrial Injuries Scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The Council’s primary role is to make recommendations about which diseases should be included in the list of diseases covered by the Industrial Injuries Scheme and the prescription criteria for those diseases.</p><p> </p><p>The legal framework underpinning the Industrial Injuries Scheme makes it clear that compensation should not be paid for a disease unless a link between a particular occupation and the disease can be established or presumed with reasonable certainty. A link is presumed where there is evidence that, on the balance of probabilities, work in the prescribed job or occupational exposure doubles the risk of developing the disease.</p><p> </p><p>The Council keeps all occupational diseases under continuous review to ensure they are in line with current scientific evidence, including chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and is always prepared to receive and consider new robust evidence from any source.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005746/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-20T17:28:13.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005746/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005746/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-12","Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department has taken to ensure that the current occupational qualification to receive industrial injuries disablement benefit for prescribed disease D12 reflects current research into the industrial causes of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","190498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005747","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-20","<p>There is work underway to review the service specifications for children and young people with cancer. This will provide an opportunity to consider how some aspects of the patient pathway may be provided more locally to reduce the travel burden for patients and their families.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the Healthcare Travel Costs Scheme which is part of the NHS Low Income Scheme allows for patients (and in certain circumstances their carers) to receive reimbursement of travel if they are in receipt of a qualifying benefit or on a low income. The NHS Low Income Scheme has helped 337,000 applicants to receive financial help with their National Health Service treatment.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005747/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-20T15:24:06.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005747/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005747/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-12","Cancer: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will set up a Young Patient Travel Fund to assist families with the travel expense of attending specialist hospitals for cancer treatment; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","190424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005748","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-20","<p>The Government is committed to reducing the harm of alcohol addiction and to ensuring there is improved availability of support for children of alcohol dependent parents.</p><p> </p><p>On 23 April 2018, the Department of Health and Social Care and the Department of Work and Pensions announced a jointly funded package of measures totalling up to £6 million to improve the availability of support for these children. Priority measures include a local authority innovation fund, national capacity building through voluntary sector organisations and additional helpline support for children. We will be announcing details of the organisations receiving funding for this work shortly.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005748/answer",,,,,"190349 ; 190350","2018-11-20T15:20:20.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005748/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005748/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-12","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what progress his Department has made on improving the availability of support and advice for children of alcoholic parents.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","190348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005749","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-20","<p>The Government is committed to reducing the harm of alcohol addiction and to ensuring there is improved availability of support for children of alcohol dependent parents.</p><p> </p><p>On 23 April 2018, the Department of Health and Social Care and the Department of Work and Pensions announced a jointly funded package of measures totalling up to £6 million to improve the availability of support for these children. Priority measures include a local authority innovation fund, national capacity building through voluntary sector organisations and additional helpline support for children. We will be announcing details of the organisations receiving funding for this work shortly.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005749/answer",,,,,"190348 ; 190350","2018-11-20T15:20:20.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005749/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005749/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-12","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what his Department’s priorities are for expanding support services for children of alcoholic parents.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","190349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005750","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-20","<p>The Government is committed to reducing the harm of alcohol addiction and to ensuring there is improved availability of support for children of alcohol dependent parents.</p><p> </p><p>On 23 April 2018, the Department of Health and Social Care and the Department of Work and Pensions announced a jointly funded package of measures totalling up to £6 million to improve the availability of support for these children. Priority measures include a local authority innovation fund, national capacity building through voluntary sector organisations and additional helpline support for children. We will be announcing details of the organisations receiving funding for this work shortly.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005750/answer",,,,,"190348 ; 190349","2018-11-20T15:20:20.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005750/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005750/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-12","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to reduce child vulnerability to alcohol-related harm.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","190350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005751","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-11-19","<p>The agenda for the EU Competitiveness Council (internal market and industry day) taking place on 29 November 2018 was agreed on 9 November by EU Ambassadors. The main items will be legislative discussions on platform-to-business relations, the Single Market Programme and the general safety of vehicles and debates on industrial policy and the future of the single market. A Written Ministerial Statement will be made shortly providing further details.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005751/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-19T15:46:05.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005751/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005751/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-11-12","EU Competitiveness Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what issues the UK Government plans to raise at the forthcoming meeting of the EU Competitiveness Council on 29 November 2018.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","190351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005752","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-11-19","<p>The UK has led international action to enhance tax transparency. This has included initiating the international work on country by country reporting during its G8 Presidency in 2013, and being the first country to commit to implement the OECD model for country by country reporting with legislation in the 2015 Finance Act.</p><p> </p><p>The issue of public country by country reporting is not on the agenda for the EU Competitiveness Council (internal market and industry day) taking place on 29 November 2018, as agreed by EU Ambassadors. The UK has no plans to raise the issue at this meeting, although we would have no objection to another Member State raising it.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government believes a multilateral approach to public country by country reporting would help ensure effective implementation.</p><p> </p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005752/answer",,,,,"190353","2018-11-19T15:32:12.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005752/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005752/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-11-12","Multinational Companies: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government would support another country putting public country by country reporting on the agenda for the EU Competitiveness Council meeting on 29 November 2018.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","190352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005753","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-11-19","<p>The UK has led international action to enhance tax transparency. This has included initiating the international work on country by country reporting during its G8 Presidency in 2013, and being the first country to commit to implement the OECD model for country by country reporting with legislation in the 2015 Finance Act.</p><p> </p><p>The issue of public country by country reporting is not on the agenda for the EU Competitiveness Council (internal market and industry day) taking place on 29 November 2018, as agreed by EU Ambassadors. The UK has no plans to raise the issue at this meeting, although we would have no objection to another Member State raising it.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government believes a multilateral approach to public country by country reporting would help ensure effective implementation.</p><p> </p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005753/answer",,,,,"190352","2018-11-19T15:32:12.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005753/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1005753/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-11-12","Multinational Companies: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans the UK Government has to raise the issue of public country by country reporting at the EU Competitiveness Council meeting on 29 November 2018.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","190353"
