"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003752","Prime Minister","false","2018-11-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the press release issued on 6 November 2018 which is available on the <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a> website:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/five-new-business-councils-to-advise-the-prime-minister-on-post-brexit-opportunities" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/five-new-business-councils-to-advise-the-prime-minister-on-post-brexit-opportunities</a></p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003752/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-14T15:36:46.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003752/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003752/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2018-11-09","Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, who the business representatives are on the five new business councils formed by the her who will advise on how to create the best business conditions in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","189651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003753","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-15","<p>a) No payments have been made;</p><p>b) Details of Arriva Rail North’s application made in accordance with the Franchise Agreement provisions concerning Industrial Action that is under consideration by the Department are subject to commercial confidentiality.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003753/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-15T11:46:46.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003753/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-11-09","Northern: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 June 2018 to Question 155260 on Northern: Industrial Disputes, what payments his Department (a) has made and (b) plans to make to Arriva Northern for revenues lost due to official industrial action.","true","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","189671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003754","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-19","<p>The Appraisal of Sustainability that accompanies the Airports National Policy Statement (NPS) provides a strategic level assessment of the potential social, economic, and environmental impacts of expansion, including on noise. The Appraisal of Sustainability makes it clear that for the purposes of this strategic level assessment, it would not be suitable to produce noise contours and therefore estimate numbers of people affected below 54dB LAeq, 16 hour for the daytime or 48 dB LAeq, 8 hours for the night time. This is because variability in aircraft position in the air at these greater distances from the airport, and airport noise being closer to background noise levels, result in a lower level of certainty.</p><p> </p><p>The Airports NPS sets out specific mitigations for aircraft noise that the Government expects to see delivered. These include the applicant putting forward plans for a noise envelope which is tailored to local priorities and includes noise performance targets. The applicant will also need to develop plans for a runway alternation scheme that provides communities affected with predictable periods of respite. The Government also expects a ban on scheduled night flights for a period of six and a half hours.</p><p> </p><p>These supporting measures will be finalised through the planning process and subject to public consultation. These will then be considered by the Planning Inspectorate and the Secretary of State in determining an application for development consent.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003754/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-19T17:00:44.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003754/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003754/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-11-09","Heathrow Airport: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of people who live in the 45Lden noise contour around Heathrow airport.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","189700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003755","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-19","<p>We will carefully consider these guidelines and their relevance to future policy.</p><p> </p><p>We will assess the supporting evidence base, as well as other relevant recent research carried out in the UK and abroad. We will be convening the Interdepartmental Group on Costs and Benefits to consider any necessary updates to relevant UK noise pollution guidelines.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003755/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-19T17:16:02.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003755/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003755/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-11-09","Noise: Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to align UK noise pollution guidelines with the new WHO guidelines.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","189701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003756","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-15","<p>a) No payments have been made;</p><p>b) Details of SWR’s application made in accordance with the Franchise Agreement provisions concerning Industrial Action that is under consideration by the Department are subject to commercial confidentiality.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003756/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-15T11:41:58.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003756/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003756/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-11-09","South Western Railway: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 25 July 2018 to Question 166508 on South Western Railway: compensation, what payments (a) have been made and (b) are planned to be made to South Western Railway for revenues lost as a result of official industrial action.","true","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","189672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003757","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-14","<p>Information about the average waiting times of appeals to the First-tier Tribunal (Social Security and Child Support) (SSCS) for (a) Personal Independence Payment (PIP) and (b) Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) is published at:</p><p>www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics</p><p> </p><p>Latest figures indicate that since PIP was introduced, 3.5 million decisions have been made up to June 2018, and of these 9% have been appealed and 4% have been overturned at Tribunals. For ESA, 3.5m ESA (post Work Capability Assessment) decisions have been made between April 2014 and March 2018 and of these 8% have been appealed and 4% have been overturned at tribunals.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003757/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-14T17:00:59.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003757/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003757/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-11-09","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average waiting time was for (a) personal independence payment and (b) employment support allowance appeal hearings in the last 12 months for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","189752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003758","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-14","<p>The information requested can be found in Annex C – Employment Tribunal Receipts Table within the published statistics and can be viewed using the following link.</p><p>www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2018</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003758/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-14T17:02:36.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003758/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003758/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-11-09","Employment Tribunal Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the number of claims made to the Employment Tribunal was by region in the 12 months to (a) 1 August 2013 and (b) 1 August 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","189753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003759","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-22","<p>MoJ funding for youth offending services is delivered through the Youth Justice Board Good Practice Grant. The changes in funding in real terms were as follows:</p><p> </p><ul><li>In the year beginning 2010: 165 million</li><li>In the year beginning 2011: 133 million</li><li>In the year beginning 2012: 118 million</li><li>In the year beginning 2013: 99 million</li><li>In the year beginning 2014: 98 million</li><li>In the year beginning 2015: 80 million</li><li>In the year beginning 2016: 74 million</li><li>In the year beginning 2017: 73 million</li><li>In the year beginning 2018: 72 million</li></ul><p> </p><p>These reductions were made in the context of wider savings made across the department. The MoJ is committed to ensuring there is sufficient funding for Youth Offending Teams whilst also ensuring public money is managed appropriately.</p><p> </p><p>YOTs continue to carry out vital work to support young people through the justice system and prevent them from entering it in the first place. The number of first time entrants to the youth justice system has fallen by 86% between 2007/08 and 2017/18, and by 14% between 2016/17 and 2017/18.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003759/answer",,,,,,"2018-11-22T16:17:44.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003759/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003759/answer","Charnwood","Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003759/answer/previousversion/85800","Biography information for Edward Argar","54","Justice","Justice","2018-11-09","Youth Offending Teams: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the real terms changes have been in his Department's total funding for youth offending teams in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","189754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003760","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-14","<p>The number of offenders sentenced to immediate custody for (a) up to and including 3 months and (b) over 3 months and up to and including 6 months for each Home Office offence code in 2017 can be viewed in the table.</p><p> </p><p>Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, who take into account all circumstances of the case, including any aggravating and mitigating factors.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst there is persuasive evidence that short custodial sentences do not help some offenders turn their backs on crime, protecting the public will always be our top priority. Under this government, the most serious offenders are more likely to go to prison, and for longer, helping protect the public and keep communities safe.</p><p> </p><p>Our message is simple – if you commit a serious offence, you should expect to go to prison. We will not reduce the prison population just to save money.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003760/answer","PQ 189755 Response Table.xlsx","PQ 189755 Response Table.xlsx","Table","Table",,"2018-11-14T16:53:37.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003760/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003760/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-11-09","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were sentenced to prison for less than (a) three months and (b) six months for each Home Office offence code in 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","189755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003761","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-19","<p>The total number of offenders sentenced to immediate custody from January to June 2018 for (a) less than 1 month, (b) 1 month to less than 3 months and (c) 3 months to 6 months, broken down by Home Office offence code, can be viewed in Table 1.</p><p> </p><p>Table 2 and Table 3 break this information down by men and women respectively.</p><p> </p><p>Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, who take into account all circumstances of the case, including any aggravating and mitigating factors.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst there is persuasive evidence that short custodial sentences do not help some offenders turn their backs on crime, protecting the public will always be our top priority. Under this government, the most serious offenders are more likely to go to prison, and for longer, helping protect the public and keep communities safe.</p><p> </p><p>Our message is simple – if you commit a serious offence, you should expect to go to prison. We will not reduce the prison population just to save money.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003761/answer","Copy of PQs 189756 189757 and 189758 Response Table.xlsx","Copy of PQs 189756 189757 and 189758 Response Table.xlsx","Table","Table","189757 ; 189758","2018-11-19T17:58:23.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003761/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1003761/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-11-09","Prison Sentences: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many men were sentenced to prison for less than (a) one month, (b) three months and (c) six months in the first six months of 2018 by Home Office offence code.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","189756"
